ow-huntergatherers-maintained-their-egalitarian-ways-three-complementary-theories%2F%5C%22%3Eactively%20be%20pulled%20down%3C%2Fa%3E%20by%20their%20community%2C%20through%20humiliation%20or%20violence%E2%80%94sometimes%20even%20to%20the%20point%20where%20the%20unhappy%20group%20murders%20the%20aspiring%20tyrant.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Indian%20subcontinent%20saw%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findia.mongabay.com%2F2021%2F02%2Fbeasts-that-once-roamed-the-indian-subcontinent-could-hold-clues-to-evolution-and-extinction%2F%5C%22%3Erelatively%20few%20megafaunal%20losses%3C%2Fa%3E%20during%20the%20global%20Late%20Quaternary%20extinction%20event%2C%20between%2050%2C000%E2%80%9310%2C000%20years%20ago.%20Losses%20included%20two%20elephant%20species%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fprehistoric-fauna.com%2FPalaeoloxodon-namadicus%5C%22%3EPalaeoloxodon%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fprehistoric-fauna.com%2FStegodon%5C%22%3EStegodon%3C%2Fa%3E%3B%20a%20hippopotamus%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fprehistoric-fauna.com%2FHexaprotodon%5C%22%3EHexaprotodon%3C%2Fa%3E%3B%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FEquus_namadicus%5C%22%3Ezebra-like%20equine%3C%2Fa%3E%3B%20and%20ostriches%20(still%20found%20in%20Africa).%20However%2C%20in%20today%E2%80%99s%20age%20of%20radical%20deforestation%20and%20industrialisation%2C%20just%20within%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fjeevoka.com%2F6-charismatic-extinct-indian-animals-in-the-last-300-years-due-to-anthropogenic-reasons%2Fs%5C%22%3Elast%20300%20years%3C%2Fa%3E%20India%20has%20already%20lost%20its%20aurochs%2C%20two%20types%20of%20rhinoceros%2C%20cheetahs%2C%20and%20civet%20cats%2C%20plus%20several%20bird%20species.%20At%20least%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.indiaspend.com%2Fearthcheck%2Fbiodiversity-collapse-whats-foiling-indias-conservation-efforts-820777%5C%22%3E97%20more%20Indian%20species%3C%2Fa%3E%20are%20presently%20on%20the%20verge%2C%20including%20its%20last%20elephants%2C%20lions%2C%20dolphins%2C%20and%20tigers.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20narcissist%20may%20also%20be%20levelled%20by%20the%20dissolution%20of%20their%20group%20through%20attrition%3A%20people%20just%20leave%20the%20braggart%E2%80%99s%20company%E2%80%94%E2%80%98vote%20with%20their%20feet%2C%E2%80%99%20as%20anthropologists%20like%20to%20say.%20Or%20they%20may%20expel%20that%20individual.%20This%20was%20possible%20because%20there%20was%20almost%20unlimited%20freedom%20of%20movement%20among%20people%20in%20nomadic%20foraging%20societies%3A%20individuals%20were%20free%20to%20walk%20away%3B%20their%20broadly%20seeded%20networks%20of%20kinship%20and%20reciprocity%20assured%20they%20had%20somewhere%20else%20to%20go%2C%20whether%20to%20join%20another%20group%20just%20across%20the%20valley%20or%20hundreds%20of%20miles%20away.%20This%20isn%E2%80%99t%20to%20suggest%20that%20no%20one%20ever%20held%20a%20leadership%20position%20or%20achieved%20some%20degree%20of%20coercive%20power%20over%20others%3B%20however%2C%20to%20the%20extent%20that%20leadership%20or%20coercive%20power%20was%20institutionalised%2C%20it%20remained%20impermanent%2C%20limited%2C%20and%20contingent.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20377px)%2085vw%2C%20377px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22377%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896.jpg%20874w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896-219x300.jpg%20219w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896-746x1024.jpg%20746w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-696598%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22518%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EIllustration%3A%20Pariplab%20Chakraborty%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20any%20case%2C%20the%20Pleistocene%20climate%20had%20always%20been%20too%20unstable%20for%20hoarding%20to%20become%20entrenched%20as%20an%20economic%20or%20social%20system.%20Before%20the%20Holocene%2C%20conditions%20had%20been%20constantly%20in%20flux%20everywhere%2C%20substantially%20rearranging%20patterns%20of%20rainfall%2C%20plant%20growth%2C%20and%20animal%20migrations%20every%20dozen%20or%20score%20generations.%20But%20it%20would%20eventually%20take%20hundreds%20of%20generations%2C%20living%20in%20stable%2C%20warm%20climatic%20conditions%20for%20societies%20to%20transition%20toward%20systems%20of%20persistent%20socioeconomic%20inequality%3A%20The%20drift%20toward%20full%20dependence%20upon%20surplus%20food%20production%20for%20storage%20and%20later%20consumption%20(%3Cem%3Edelayed-return%20economies%3C%2Fem%3E)%20itself%20took%20thousands%20of%20years.%20And%20after%20that%2C%20the%20ossification%20of%20rigid%20social%20hierarchies%20took%20thousands%20more.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20for%20most%20of%20humanity%E2%80%99s%20time%20on%20Earth%2C%20such%20a%20length%20of%20stable%2C%20temperate%20conditions%2C%20as%20in%20the%20Holocene%2C%20had%20never%20occurred.%20And%20so%20for%20nearly%20all%20of%20human%20experience%2C%20immediate-return%20economies%20and%20fluidly%20egalitarian%20structures%20or%20fluctuating%20hierarchies%20defined%20the%20baseline%20social%20context%20of%20ongoing%20human%20evolution%2C%20as%20human%20knowledge%20systems%2C%20interrelationships%2C%20and%20cultures%20grew%20thicker%20and%20more%20complex.%20Until%20at%20least%20the%20mid-Holocene%2C%20roughly%20five%20thousand%20years%20ago%2C%20all%20human%20societies%20functioned%20primarily%20on%20the%20basis%20of%20mutual%20aid%2C%20grounded%20in%20social%20bonds%20and%20cooperative%20cultural%20norms%2C%20and%20deeply%20connected%20to%20the%20health%20of%20their%20home%20ecosystems.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESomething%20has%20certainly%20changed%20in%20more%20recent%20history.%20Few%20people%20today%20live%20in%20the%20kinds%20of%20balanced%20and%20egalitarian%20societies%20that%20were%20ordinary%20for%2099%20percent%20of%20our%20time%20on%20Earth.%20Instead%2C%20most%20people%20today%20are%20stuck%20within%20the%20deeply%20entrenched%20system%20of%20socioeconomic%20hierarchy%20that%20is%20our%20modern%2C%20industrial%20civilisation.%20This%20same%20global%20system%20has%20largely%20dismantled%20healthy%20ecosystem%20functioning%20across%20large%20portions%20of%20the%20Earth%2C%20rerouting%20the%20flows%20of%20energy%20and%20materials%20away%20from%20benefiting%20ecosystem%20robustness%2C%20but%20instead%20toward%20feeding%20the%20desires%20of%20our%20single%20species.%20There%20are%20now%20so%20many%20humans%20that%20we%E2%80%99re%20literally%20crowding%20out%20other%20forms%20of%20life%2C%20as%20we%20destroy%20their%20habitats%20for%20our%20cities%2C%20farms%2C%20pasturelands%2C%20mines%2C%20dams%2C%20roads%2C%20and%20other%20infrastructures.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBy%2045%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20South%20and%20Southeast%20Asia%20were%20already%20home%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.0810842106%5C%22%3Emost%20of%20the%20world%E2%80%99s%20people%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Around%2035%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20when%20new%20stone%20toolmaking%20technologies%20jumped%20in%20sophistication%2C%20indigenous%20South%20Asian%20populations%20began%20growing%20even%20faster.%20Perhaps%20this%20surge%20of%20humans%20caused%20the%20local%20megafaunal%20extinctions.%20Further%20innovations%20in%20tool%20technologies%2C%20the%20spread%20of%20cereal%20agriculture%2C%20and%20patriarchy%20have%20each%20played%20a%20role%20in%20rapid%20population%20growth%20at%20various%20times%20since%20then%2C%20such%20that%20South%20Asia%20has%20remained%20among%20the%20most%20populous%20regions%20in%20the%20world.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20human%20enterprise%20now%20claims%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencedirect.com%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS1439179122000949%5C%22%3E25%25%20of%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20net%20primary%20productivity%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%94that%20is%2C%20the%20total%20amount%20of%20the%20sun%E2%80%99s%20energy%20converted%20into%20food%20by%20plants%E2%80%94an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.1211349110%5C%22%3Eamount%20that%E2%80%99s%20doubled%3C%2Fa%3E%20over%20the%20last%20century%20alone.%20And%20since%20sunlight%20falls%20at%20a%20finite%20daily%20rate%2C%20all%20the%20other%20living%20beings%E2%80%94who%20continue%20to%20subsist%20within%20the%20economics%20of%20immediate-return%20energy%20flows%E2%80%94have%20less%20energy%20to%20live%20on.%20We%E2%80%99re%20fundamentally%20changing%20the%20energy%20and%20material%20flows%20of%20our%20biosphere%20in%20a%20way%20that%20results%20in%20a%20%3Cem%3Emassive%3C%2Fem%3E%20increase%20of%20humans%20and%20our%20domesticates%E2%80%94alongside%20a%20commensurate%20diminishment%20of%20%3Cem%3Eall%20other%20life%3C%2Fem%3E.%20In%20fact%2C%20today%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Famp.theguardian.com%2Fenvironment%2F2018%2Fmay%2F21%2Fhuman-race-just-001-of-all-life-but-has-destroyed-over-80-of-wild-mammals-study%3FCMP%3Dshare_btn_tw%26__twitter_impression%3Dtrue%5C%22%3Ehumans%20make%20up%2036%25%20by%20weight%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20all%20the%20mammals%20on%20the%20planet%2C%20while%20elephants%2C%20whales%2C%20tigers%2C%20bears%E2%80%94almost%20every%20wild%20animal%20you%20might%20think%20of%E2%80%94are%20fast%20disappearing%2C%20altogether%20accounting%20for%20only%204%20percent%20of%20mammalian%20biomass.%20This%20is%20estimated%20to%20be%20an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.weforum.org%2Fagenda%2F2021%2F04%2Fmammals-human-agriculture-charts%2F%5C%22%3E85%25%20reduction%20of%20land-dwelling%2C%20wild%20mammalian%20biomass%3C%2Fa%3E%20since%20modern%20humans%20first%20left%20Africa%20and%2C%20given%20the%20decimations%20of%20whaling%2C%20this%20figure%20would%20be%20substantially%20higher%20if%20marine%20mammals%20were%20included.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEven%20so%2C%20during%20the%20same%20span%20of%20time%2C%20the%20%3Cem%3Eoverall%3C%2Fem%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.weforum.org%2Fagenda%2F2021%2F04%2Fmammals-human-agriculture-charts%2F%5C%22%3Emammalian%20biomass%20has%20multiplied%3C%2Fa%3E%20by%20nine%20times%2C%20due%20to%20the%20massive%20expansion%20of%20domesticated%20animals%2C%20especially%20pigs%20and%20cows.%20Today%2C%20birds%20farmed%20for%20human%20consumption%E2%80%94mostly%20chickens%E2%80%94make%20up%20almost%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.1711842115%5C%22%3Ethree%20times%20the%20biomass%20of%20wild%20birds%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Human%20activity%20has%20reduced%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fenvironment%2F2020%2Fdec%2F09%2Fhuman-made-materials-now-outweigh-earths-entire-biomass-study%5C%22%3Eplant%20biomass%20by%20half%3C%2Fa%3E%20since%20the%20dawn%20of%20agriculture%20and%20obliterated%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fenvironment%2F2018%2Foct%2F30%2Fhumanity-wiped-out-animals-since-1970-major-report-finds%5C%22%3E60%20percent%20of%20all%20mammals%2C%20birds%2C%20fish%2C%20and%20reptiles%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20just%20the%C2%A0past%2060%20years.%20And%20the%20rate%20of%20annihilation%20is%20%3Cem%3Eaccelerating%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20984px)%2061vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2045vw%2C%20600px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25113249%2FDecline-of-the-worlds-wild-mammals.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20